am, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Tatesham, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1405–1480":"1405–1480","1400–1485":"1400–1485","1418–Female":"1418–Deceased","1425–1489":"1425–1489","1448–1497":"1448–1497","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1497":"1497","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","August 1425":"August 1425","1405":"1405","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Fawnes Manor, Tatesham, Wrotham, Tonbridge and Malling, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Wrotham, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Tatesham, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"McCoy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’, originally the name of a pagan god. Thus it has the same origin as   McGee  ,   McKay  , and   McKee  . It has sometimes been Anglicized as   Hughes  .","History: The McCoy clan of KY, led by Randolph McCoy, was involved in one of the bitterest mountain feuds, with the Hatfield clan of WV, from the Civil War to the end of the 19th century. The expression ‘the real McCoy’ probably originated with an American boxer, Norman Selby (1873–1940), who adopted the name “Kid McCoy” to distinguish himself from another fighter of the same name."],"variants":[{"name":"McKoy","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McCoy  ."]},{"name":"McGee","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Aoidh</b> or <b>Mag Aodha</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’, originally the name of a pagan god. See also   McCoy  ."]},{"name":"McGue","meanings":["Irish (northern): variant of   McCoy  . Compare   McHugh  ."]},{"name":"McQuay","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McCoy  ."]},{"name":"McCay","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: variant of   McCoy  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":50,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice McCoy was born in 1405, in Wrotham, Kent, England. She married Talran Tatesham Esq. in 1424, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1480, in Kent, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1405–1480":"1405–1480","1400–1485":"1400–1485","1418–Female":"1418–Surnud","1425–1489":"1425–1489","1448–1497":"1448–1497","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1497":"1497","1485":"1485","1480